## Testing standards

This document owns test selection, test structure, assertions, fixture design
and test pruning for compiler work.

It does not define the final validation command. For completion gates, read
`docs/src/docs/codebase/style-guide/validation.bd`.

The primary goal is end-to-end language and artifact correctness. Prefer real
usage patterns and complete Beanstalk snippets over narrow implementation-shaped
tests.

### Default testing preference

Integration tests written in Beanstalk are the default for user-visible language behaviour. They exercise the real compiler path and usually provide the strongest regression coverage.

- Prefer integration coverage for user-visible language behaviour
- Add or update unit tests only where subsystem-local behaviour genuinely benefits from them
- Avoid redundant fixtures that assert the same behaviour in slightly different forms
- Prefer meaningful end-to-end cases over brittle implementation-shaped assertions
- When backend or runtime behaviour matters, strengthen artifact assertions where goldens alone are too vague

### Supporting rules

- Prefer externally observable behaviour over implementation detail.
- Use unit tests for hidden invariants that integration output cannot inspect.
- Use one clear primary test owner per behaviour.
- Do not create multiple fixtures that prove the same contract without a distinct stage or backend reason.
- Prefer realistic end-to-end snippets.
- Tests should remain understandable without reading the implementation first.
- Do not make exact internal layout contractual unless that layout is the invariant.

### Test ownership

[table:
    [th:
        [: **Behavior**]
        [: **Owner**]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Pure data or invariant behavior]
        [: Focused unit test near the owning subsystem]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Compiler-stage invariant]
        [: Stage-local unit test naming the invariant]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Stage-boundary orchestration]
        [: Minimal pipeline/build smoke test]
    ]

    [td:
        [: User-facing language behavior]
        [: Integration case under `tests/cases/`]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Backend artifact behavior]
        [: Backend-specific artifact assertions or contractual goldens]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Side-table or hidden compiler fact]
        [: Focused unit test if external output cannot expose it]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Cross-backend semantic parity]
        [: One integration input with backend-specific assertions]
    ]
]

Each behavior should have one primary owner. Secondary coverage is justified only when it protects a distinct boundary, target, diagnostic lane or internal invariant.

### Test location and module layout

- Tests do not live in production implementation files.
- Module-specific tests belong under the module's test directory, for example:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    src/compiler_frontend/hir/tests/
]

- End-to-end or multi-module Rust harness tests belong under:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    src/compiler_tests/
]

- Language and project integration cases belong under:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    tests/cases/
]

- Test-only utilities should live with the tests that own them.
- Do not create broad shared test utility modules for one or two callers.
- Split cross-stage test support only when actual ownership boundaries justify it.

### Unit tests

Retain unit tests for:

- pure data invariants
- impossible states
- side-table facts
- transfer rules
- backend planning policy not observable from artifacts
- narrow parser or formatter algorithms

Prefer integration tests for user-visible behavior.
Once a subsystem is stable, prune superseded unit tests.
Rewrite obsolete tests rather than preserving old API shapes.
A unit test should name the invariant it protects.
Do not use unit coverage as a substitute for an end-to-end case when user behavior changed.

### Integration cases

- `bean tests` runs the integration test runner.
- Use real Beanstalk snippets.
- Each canonical case is one self-contained scenario directory.
- Keep helper source files inside the owning case's `input/` directory.
- Do not let helper files become unintended standalone cases.
- Add strong output assertions where behavior is visible.
- Prefer top-level templates to simulate output.
- Avoid `io.line(...)` unless console behavior is itself under test.

For new type-system syntax, include:

- positive usage
- value/type namespace misuse
- import visibility
- duplicates
- cross-file resolution
- target/backend rejection where relevant

Canonical fixture shape:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    tests/cases/
    ├── manifest.toml
    └── case_name/
        ├── input/
        │   ├── main.bst
        │   └── helper.bst
        ├── expect.toml
        └── golden/
            ├── html/
            └── html_wasm/
]

- `manifest.toml` may order or tag cases during fixture migrations.
- One case folder owns all inputs and expectations for that scenario.

### Diagnostics assertions

- Ordinary source/config/import/type/rule/borrow failures should assert stable `diagnostic_codes`.
- Add rendered message fragments only when wording or rendered labels are part of the contract.
- Infrastructure-boundary tests may assert infrastructure `ErrorType`.
- Preserve source location assertions where location behavior is important.
- Do not use full rendered diagnostic snapshots when a stable code and structured assertion are sufficient.
- Do not weaken a diagnostic case into a generic "must fail" assertion.

### Backend matrices and artifact assertions

Use one `expect.toml` per case with backend-specific assertion blocks.

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    entry = "."

    [backends.html]
    mode = "success"
    warnings = "forbid"
    artifacts_must_not_exist = ["unexpected.html"]

    [backends.html_wasm]
    mode = "success"
    warnings = "forbid"

    [[backends.html_wasm.artifact_assertions]]
    path = "page.wasm"
    kind = "wasm"
    validate_wasm = true
    must_export = ["memory", "bst_str_ptr", "bst_str_len", "bst_release"]
]

- Use backend-specific blocks within one case.
- Store strict goldens in:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    golden/<backend>/
]

- Use artifact assertions for structure: file presence, Wasm validity, exports, imports, expected snippets, absence of forbidden output.
- Use `artifacts_must_not_exist` for success cases whose contract requires an exact normalized output path to be absent. Paths reported as `NotBuilt` are ignored because they were never emitted.
- Use strict goldens only where exact emitted text is contractual.
- Prefer semantic or rendered-output assertions for behavior-first cases.
- Strengthen artifact assertions when a golden can pass while structural behavior is wrong.
- Do not require unsupported backends to succeed merely for matrix symmetry. Assert the intended rejection contract.

### HIR and internal-IR assertions

- Assert semantic relationships rather than incidental indexes.
- Prefer branch joins, merge-local relationships, jump arguments, region ownership, side-table keys, stable call targets and required operation kinds.
- Avoid exact block IDs or vector offsets unless exact layout is the invariant.
- Do not make temporary lowering order part of the public test contract.
- For HIR validation, distinguish malformed-HIR invariant tests from user-facing source diagnostic tests.

### Fixtures and temporary files

- Prefer `tempfile::tempdir()` for temporary directories and files.
- Use unmanaged paths only when the test intentionally owns cleanup.
- Keep fixtures local to their owner.
- Do not commit generated `dev/` or `release/` outputs from test or benchmark projects.
- Avoid shared fixture builders that hide important source shape.

### Pruning and duplicate coverage

- Remove tests tied only to deleted implementation paths.
- Avoid several fixtures that differ only cosmetically.
- Preserve duplicates only when they protect different stages, diagnostic reasons, backends, source locations or artifact contracts.
- Localize one-caller fixtures.
- When two tests overlap, identify the primary owner and either merge them, narrow each to a distinct invariant or delete the weaker one.
- Do not preserve obsolete fixtures for historical compatibility.

### Benchmarks are not correctness tests

Benchmark fixtures are performance evidence, not correctness coverage.

Do not use benchmark coverage as a substitute for unit or integration tests.
Negative diagnostics belong in `tests/cases`, not benchmark fixtures.

Use `bench-check` to detect broad performance regressions after correctness has
already been established by ordinary tests.

### Testing checklist

Before considering test coverage complete, check:

- The behavior has one clear primary test owner.
- User-visible behavior has end-to-end integration coverage.
- Internal-only invariants have focused unit coverage where needed.
- Failure cases assert stable diagnostic codes.
- Rendered text is asserted only when it is contractual.
- Backend behavior uses the narrowest useful artifact assertions.
- Goldens are used only where exact output is a contract.
- HIR tests avoid incidental block and local numbering.
- Multi-file fixtures remain inside one case directory.
- Temporary files use owned cleanup.
- No benchmark fixture is being used as a correctness substitute.
- Redundant or obsolete coverage has been removed.
